name: Tham Phra
Access_description: This is an isolated sandstone hill 15 km west-north-west of Amnat Charoen, 2 km east of the border with Yasothon. Wat Phu Champa is to the south of the hill.

name: Tham Seang Kaeo
Access_description: From Amnat Charoen take the H202 east to the Lao Phraun tambon office then turn north and continue for about 6 km to the temple which is on top is a hill to the north of the Huai Mak Mon reservoir. The temple is in the Phu Sing-Phu Pha Phung National Park.
Description_description: The site is a sandstone rock shelter.

name: Tham Saeng Phet I
Access_description: From Amnat Charoen take the H202 east for 12 km and then turn north on the H3010 for 3 km to a small road which leads up the hill to the large temple of Wat Tham Saeng Phet Bon. The hill is to the west of the Huai Si Tho reservoir.
Description_description: The large sandstone cave, where the famous meditation monk Ajarn Chah once lived, is to the north of the temple buildings and now houses a Buddha statue.

name: Tham Bing
Access_description: The hill is halfway between Kham Khuean Kaeo and Ban Lao Yang Chom, 5.5 km west of the H3006.
Description_description: Tham Bing is a series of sandstone rock shelters with a pool of holy water.

name: Tham Klaeb
Access_description: The temple is on top of a small isolated hill 4 km north of Nong Hai.
Description_description: In the temple grounds there are rock shelters in a 15 m high cliff.

name: Tham Phra Phu Wang Thong
Access_description: The cave is situated in the hills 4.5 km north-east of Ban Na Sa Ard.

name: Tham Hin Hua Nak Phu Kaset
Access_description: The temple is at the top of the escarpment on the southern edge of a hill 3 km north-north-east of Nong Hai. Access is via a road from the northern side of the hill.

name: Tham Pha Nang An
Access_description: The co-ordinates place the cave on a hill on the eastern shore of the Huai Sai reservoir, 3.5km north-west of Kham Phon.

name: Tham Don Nok Yung
Access_description: The co-ordinates place the cave 4.5 km north of the H202 from Pathum Ratchawongsa, near a temple on the south-west end of an isolated hill to the north of Ban Thaweepol.

name: Tham Yao Badan
Access_description: The campsite is on the southern slopes of the Phu Sing-Phu Pha Phung National Park, 900 m north of the turning to the Phu Sing Air Force communications station and 1.5 km north of Kam Po Kaeo. The cave is signposted in Thai from the H202 8 km east of the turning to Amnat Charoen.
Description_description: The cave is large enough to have sheltered communist insurgents. John Dunkley was unable to find this cave in 2015, but did note a lot of exposed sandstone pseudokarst similar to that at Phu Hin Rong Kla in Phitsanulok.

name: Tham Chalam
Access_description: The co-ordinates place the temple on the plain 1.3 km south of the Huai Mak Mon reservoir and 2.75 km north of the H202.

name: Tham Kho Non
Access_description: From Amnat Charoen take the H202 east for 12 km and then turn north for 3 km to a small road which leads up the hill to the large temple of Wat Tham Saeng Phet Bon. The hill is to the west of the Huai Si Tho reservoir. This cave is not far from Tham Saeng Phet III, at the base of a cliff in the forest.
Description_description: The rock shelter is 40 m wide, 6 m high and 15 m deep. A hut has been built in the rock shelter.

name: Tham Seeha Wanaram
Access_description: The co-ordinates place the temple in flat country 1 km east of the Phuttaautayan recervoir and 4 km north-east of Amnat Charoen.

name: Tham Saeng Phet II
Access_description: From Amnat Charoen take the H202 east for 12 km and then turn north on the H3010 for 3 km to a small road which leads up the hill to the large temple of Wat Tham Saeng Phet Bon. The hill is to the west of the Huai Si Tho reservoir.
Description_description: This is a small cave in sandstone.

name: Tham Thep Muni
Access_description: The campsite is on the southern slopes of the Phu Sing-Phu Pha Phung National Park, 600 m north of the turning to the Phu Sing Air Force communications station and 1 km north of Kam Po Kaeo.

name: Tham Saeng Phet III
Access_description: From Amnat Charoen take the H202 east for 12 km and then turn north on the H3010 for 3 km to a small road which leads up the hill to the large temple of Wat Tham Saeng Phet Bon. The hill is to the west of the Huai Si Tho reservoir.
Description_description: The entrance, which is 4.8 m wide, is completely blocked up, except for a metal door. It opens to a horizontal passage that ends sloping slightly upwards and is 6 m wide. The cave is in sandstone.

name: Nong Tham
Description_description: There may not be a cave as there does not appear to be limestone in the area.

name: Ban Nong Tham
Access_description: The village is 1 km east of the H3064, on the border with Singburi.
Description_description: There may not be a cave as there does not appear to be limestone in the area.

name: Tham Pho
Access_description: Phu Wua Lang Tham Pho is marked on maps at the northern end of a long sandstone mountain of the Phu Wua Wildlife Sanctuary.

name: Tham Sung
Access_description: Phu Wua Lang Tham Sung is highest point in the wildlife reserve at 448 m and it is at the south-eastern end of the large sandstone mountain that forms the Phu Wua Wildlife Santuary.

name: Tham Kaew
Access_description: Phu Tok is located 27km along the H222 from Bueng Kan heading towards Si Wilai, then going 20km east.

name: Tham Lek Lai
Access_description: Phu Tok is located 27km along the H222 from Bueng Kan heading towards Si Wilai, then going 20km east.
Description_description: Wat Pha Tok is a renowned forest wat founded in 1968 by Phra Ajan Chuan Kunchettho. The wat is famous for the wooden walkways that ascend the 150 m high outcrop of eolian sandstone in seven levels and took five years to build. These seven levels represent the seven levels of Buddhist enlightment.

name: Tham Ruesi
Access_description: Phu Tok is located 27km along the H222 from Bueng Kan heading towards Si Wilai, then going 20km east.
Description_description: Wat Pha Tok is a renowned forest wat founded in 1968 by Phra Ajan Chuan Kunchettho. The wat is famous for the wooden walkways that ascend the 150m high outcrop of eolian sandstone in seven levels and took five years to build. These seven levels represent the seven levels of Buddhist enlightment.  The sandstone is Upper Cretaceous and is known as the Phu Tok Formation.

name: Cave BK0006
Access_description: A cave is marked on a 1:250,000 geological map between Tham Pho and Tham Sung.

name: Tham Sri Thon
Access_description: Wat Sawang Arom is in Pak Khat, 500 m east of the H212.
Description_description: Dunkley mentions a report of a possible cave at this location.

name: Tham Chan
Access_description: The temple is on a low hill just to the west of Ban Kham Phai, which is on the H5004.
Description_description: The cave is high up, without water, and is a labyrinthine network of natural rock formations that have been utilized as temples.

name: Tham Fun
Access_description: From Bueng Kan take the H212 east for 5.3 km and then turn south (Tham Fun and the Tham Fun waterfall are signposted).  Follow this road for 2.75 km to the park office and then it is a 1.5 km walk to the waterfall.
Description_description: A couple of websites describe the cave as being 'cool and refreshing' and 'peaceful' so there might be a proper cave here.

name: Tham Chan Pha
Access_description: From Ban Thung Sai Chok take the track signposted to Tham Chum Chang and Tham Sok Chang to the Chanaen waterfall checkpoint, which is 3.5 km from the H3024 and 1km north of Tham Sok Chang. The cave is a 500 m walk from here.

name: Tham Charoen
Access_description: The village is on the H5004, 14km east of the H2095.

name: Tham Phrai
Access_description: From the Bung Khla ranger station take the nature trail to the top of the escarpment. From here follow the path south. There are signs 800 m and 450 m from the cave, but on a quick visit in January 2011 the cave was not found.

name: Tham Phra Wanaram
Access_description: The forest wat is near the Mae Nam Mae Khong, 1 km east of Ban Tai and 7 km north-west of the H212, along a secondary road from Pak Khat.

name: Tham Chong
Access_description: The wat is near the Mae Nam Mae Khong river, 6 km north-west of the H212, along a secondary road from Pak Khat.

name: Tham Khieo Sa-un
Access_description: The temple is 2 km north-east of Ban Loet Sin, in tambon Kamnadee.

name: Tham Phra
Access_description: The temple is 1.5 km south-east of the H5004 near Ban Huai Dok Mai.

name: Tham Sala Nam Yen
Access_description: The camp site is located 4.5 km west of Ban Nong Yao, on the eastern flank of the long, narrow Phu Sing sandstone mountain.

name: Tham Phra
Access_description: The temple is on the southern end of Phu Wua mountain, 5 km north of Ban Non Samran in tambon Sok Kam.
Description_description: This is a rock shelter which is formed in sandstone.

name: Tham Si Chom Phu
Access_description: The temple is on a low hill to the north-west Ban Tham Charoen which is on the H5004, 14km east of the H2095.

name: Tham Bucha
Access_description: This famous forest wat is located on the south-western escarpment of the Phu Wua Wildlife Sanctuary. It is accessed by a 5.25 km road which turns east off the H2013 in Ban Don Siat.

name: Tham Khong Phu Wua
Access_description: The camp site is on the southern end of Phu Wua mountain, 3.5 km north of Ban Non Samran in tambon Sok Kam.

name: Tham Noi Nam Thip
Access_description: The camp site is 9km east of Si Wilai and the H222, at the base of the western flank of the long and narrow Phu Sing sandstone mountain.
Description_description: There are rock shelters in sandstone with percolating water.

name: Tham Pladuk
Access_description: The camp site is 9km east of Si Wilai and the H222, at the base of the western flank of the long and narrow Phu Sing sandstone mountain and 1.75km north of Tham Noi Nam Thip.

name: Tham Saen Chang Lai
Access_description: The wat is 3 km east of Ban Thung Sai Chok and is signed off the H3024. From the temple a very good path and bridges lead to the rock shelter at the base of a long, low cliff.
Description_description: This is an impressively large rock shelter, formed at the base of a sandstone cliff. It is about 25 m deep, 250 m long and 5 m above the valley floor. It has been developed by monks as a shrine.

name: Tham Saeng Dao
Access_description: The camp site is located 4 km west of Ban Nong Yao, on the eastern flank of the long, narrow Phu Sing sandstone mountain.

name: Tham Pha Daeng
Access_description: This wat is sign posted as being 2km east of Ban Rai, along the same road as Tham In See.

name: Tham Chum Chang
Access_description: The cave is sign posted off the H3024 in Ban Thung Sai Chok, along the same road as Tham Sok Chang.

name: Tham Sua
Access_description: The wat is 750 m south of the H212, between Ban A-Hong and Ban Khai Si.

name: Tham Phra Punyaram
Access_description: The temple, shown on a GIS map, is in Ban Sok Phok on the north-eastern shore of the Bueng Khlong Long reservoir. No hills are apparent in this area on Google Earth.

name: Tham Saeng Tham
Access_description: The temple is at the foot of the escarpment 1.5 km north-east of Ban Dong Chomphu on the H2026.

name: Tham Khaen
Access_description: The temple is at the foot of the escarpment 2 km east of Ban Dong Chomphu on the H2026.

name: Tham In See
Access_description: The wat is sign posted as being 5 km east of Ban Rai. Follow the laterite road for about 5 km through the rubber plantations to the forest temple at the foot of the escarpment.
Description_description: Behind the main building at the foot of the cliff there is a hole under a large sandstone boulder that has behind developed into a small shrine.

name: Tham Ajarn Chuan
Access_description: Phu Thok is located 27 km along the H222 from Bueng Kan heading towards Si Wilai, then going 20 km east.
Description_description: This is the main shrine cave on the fifth level. The cave is about 10 m deep and 50 m wide.

name: Tham Wihan Kot
Access_description: Phu Thok is located 27 km along the H222 from Bueng Kan heading towards Si Wilai, then going 20 km east. This is the large cave on the fifth level just west of the main shrine.
Description_description: This is a large cave formed on a joint. It is egg timer shaped with two tubes above one another, extending back about 25 m.

name: Tham Wihan Yao
Access_description: Phu Thok is located 27 km along the H222 from Bueng Kan heading towards Si Wilai, then going 20 km east. This is the wide rock shelter to the east of the main shrine cave and Tham Wihan Kot
Description_description: This rock shelter is about 10 m deep and 50 m wide.

name: Tham Sok Chang
Access_description: The temple is sign posted off the H3024 in Ban Thung Sai Chok, along the same road as Tham Chum Chang. It is at the base of the Phu Wua escarpment.

name: Tham Mongkhon
Access_description: The temple is at the southern end of Ban Lao Yai, tambon Si Samran, on the H3002.

name: Tham Pha Daeng
Access_description: The temple is at the base of the massif at the southern end of the 350 m high Pha Daeng cliff, 5 km east of the H2026 at Bueng Khong Long.
